%I A396055 #4 May 18 2026 19:58:41
%S A396055 0,0,0,2,8472,2107750
%N A396055 Number of relations R on an n-element set such that the transitive closure of R has exactly six elements more than R.
%C A396055 Equivalently, a(n) is the number of binary relations R on an n-set for which exactly six ordered pairs must be adjoined to obtain a transitive relation, i.e. |closure(R) \ R| = 6.
%e A396055 For n = 0, 1, 2 every relation R on [n] satisfies |closure(R) \ R| <= 4 < 6, so a(0) = a(1) = a(2) = 0.
%e A396055 For n = 3, a(3) = 2: the only two relations on a 3-set whose transitive closure is six ordered pairs larger are the directed 3-cycles R_1 = {(1,2),(2,3),(3,1)} and R_2 = {(1,3),(3,2),(2,1)}; the transitive closure of each is the universal relation on {1,2,3} (all 9 ordered pairs), and so 9 - 3 = 6 pairs must be added.
%Y A396055 Cf. A006905, A395083, A395919, A395920.
%K A396055 nonn,hard,more,new
